11
00:00:53,454 --> 00:00:55,387
whether heading across the country          

12
00:00:55,389 --> 00:00:59,325
or taking a weekend getaway, people love to travel.     

13
00:00:59,327 --> 00:01:01,127
regardless of the destination, 

14
00:01:01,129 --> 00:01:04,397
it's impossible to leave home without luggage.        

15
00:01:04,399 --> 00:01:06,799
luggage is made from all kinds of materials,         

16
00:01:06,801 --> 00:01:09,468
including wood, metal, plastic,

17
00:01:09,470 --> 00:01:12,104
hi-tech polycarbonates, and leather.          

18
00:01:14,475 --> 00:01:18,410
not all leather overnight bags are created equal.       

19
00:01:18,412 --> 00:01:20,546
this dark brown bag was constructed        

20
00:01:20,548 --> 00:01:22,848
with the capacity to hold water.

21
00:01:25,419 --> 00:01:28,086
the process starts with full-grain hides,     

22
00:01:28,088 --> 00:01:31,823
chrome-tanned by an outside facility.    

23
00:01:31,825 --> 00:01:33,893
chrome-tanning is an effective treatment           

24
00:01:33,895 --> 00:01:37,830
which allows the leather to become more water resistant.

25
00:01:37,832 --> 00:01:41,167
this bag is constructed from a single piece of leather,

26
00:01:41,169 --> 00:01:44,770
making it more durable and water-tight.        

27
00:01:44,772 --> 00:01:47,506
first, a leather worker uses a template        

28
00:01:47,508 --> 00:01:49,642
to cut out the shape of the bag.

29
00:01:49,644 --> 00:01:54,980
♪          

30
00:01:54,982 --> 00:02:00,119
♪          

31
00:02:00,121 --> 00:02:02,455
he uses the machine to shave the edges       

32
00:02:02,457 --> 00:02:05,991
off the piece of leather in a process called sciving,  

33
00:02:05,993 --> 00:02:09,461
which prepares the leather for folding and sewing.    

34
00:02:09,463 --> 00:02:10,863
using a hole punch,      

35
00:02:10,865 --> 00:02:13,465
another craftsman taps the series of openings  

36
00:02:13,467 --> 00:02:18,471
for riveting on buckles and other attachments.     

37
00:02:18,473 --> 00:02:20,940
the holes will prevent the opening from ripping.   

38
00:02:20,942 --> 00:02:26,479
♪          

39
00:02:26,481 --> 00:02:29,482
next, a leather worker uses a template to mark    

40
00:02:29,484 --> 00:02:32,652
where he'll apply       
a strip of glue to the top edge.

41
00:02:37,291 --> 00:02:41,093
he attaches a polyester strip to the bottom edge of the glue 

42
00:02:43,363 --> 00:02:46,365
and spreads more glue on top of the polyester.    

43
00:02:49,170 --> 00:02:52,437
then he folds and hammers the top portion of the leather 

44
00:02:52,439 --> 00:02:56,575
over onto the polyester strip. 

45
00:02:56,577 --> 00:02:58,044
once complete,         

46
00:02:58,046 --> 00:03:01,247
the leather worker trims the edges of the polyester.  

47
00:03:03,451 --> 00:03:06,985
the leather is then placed into
a machine known as a clicker, 

48
00:03:06,987 --> 00:03:11,056
to stamp out the bag straps and other leather components. 

49
00:03:11,058 --> 00:03:16,395
♪          

50
00:03:16,397 --> 00:03:19,798
the clicker works by applying 25 tons of pressure      

51
00:03:19,800 --> 00:03:23,469
to custom-made dyes.      

52
00:03:23,471 --> 00:03:26,338
the shoulder pad is one of 22 pieces of leather      

53
00:03:26,340 --> 00:03:28,074
that will complete the bag.  

54
00:03:30,878 --> 00:03:33,145
a craftsperson glues a foam rectangle        

55
00:03:33,147 --> 00:03:35,548
between two layers of leather. 

56
00:03:35,550 --> 00:03:40,485
this type of glue won't bubble in hot temperatures.      

57
00:03:40,487 --> 00:03:43,555
chrome-tanned hide is tough stuff,        

58
00:03:43,557 --> 00:03:46,024
so manufacturers use a heated stamp         

59
00:03:46,026 --> 00:03:48,194
to brand the leather with their logo.        

60
00:03:51,165 --> 00:03:53,632
a leather worker uses a sewing machine        

61
00:03:53,634 --> 00:03:57,236
to piece together multiple parts of the leather. 

62
00:03:57,238 --> 00:04:00,039
the stitching perforations weakens the leather,      

63
00:04:00,041 --> 00:04:03,441
so for added strength,     
the craftsman uses a heavy gauge

64
00:04:03,443 --> 00:04:07,580
continuous-filament polyester thread.       

65
00:04:07,582 --> 00:04:11,250
next, a craftsman attaches the buckles.          

66
00:04:11,252 --> 00:04:14,253
he places one steel rivet in each buckle piece      

67
00:04:14,255 --> 00:04:16,922
and secures it into place.   

68
00:04:16,924 --> 00:04:19,725
he leaves the remaining rivets out to accommodate       

69
00:04:19,727 --> 00:04:21,059
the sewing machine,      

70
00:04:21,061 --> 00:04:23,461
which will reinforce the attachment.        

71
00:04:23,463 --> 00:04:27,800
the buckles are made of high strength 316 stainless steel. 

72
00:04:27,802 --> 00:04:34,073
♪          

73
00:04:34,075 --> 00:04:38,343
a craftsman attaches a piece of
plastic to reinforce the handle

74
00:04:38,345 --> 00:04:41,680
and prevent the leather from becoming misshapen over time. 

75
00:04:41,682 --> 00:04:48,487
♪          

76
00:04:48,489 --> 00:04:52,958
once he's glued in pieces of plastic to each handle opening,

77
00:04:52,960 --> 00:04:57,296
the leather worker finishes all the seams.    

78
00:04:57,298 --> 00:05:00,432
this type of continuous-filament
polyester thread        

79
00:05:00,434 --> 00:05:04,102
is the same kind that is used to sew parachutes together.  

80
00:05:04,104 --> 00:05:09,842
♪          

81
00:05:09,844 --> 00:05:13,178
next, a craftswoman cleans the completed bag       

82
00:05:13,180 --> 00:05:15,247
and applies a generous amount of leather milk        

83
00:05:15,249 --> 00:05:17,515
to condition the leather.   

84
00:05:17,517 --> 00:05:19,518
the leather milk is made of all-natural,    

85
00:05:19,520 --> 00:05:21,654
non-toxic ingredients.     

86
00:05:21,656 --> 00:05:26,925
♪          

87
00:05:26,927 --> 00:05:30,862
the craftswoman uses a torch to singe off any stray hairs  

88
00:05:30,864 --> 00:05:34,867
before the strap is attached to
a set of upper or lower d-rings.

89
00:05:37,538 --> 00:05:39,404
this first little bag can now be worn        

90
00:05:39,406 --> 00:05:43,075
as a backpack or a shoulder bag.

91
00:05:43,077 --> 00:05:45,945
stylish and durable, this leather overnight bag   

92
00:05:45,947 --> 00:05:47,613
is built to hold your stuff  

93
00:05:47,615 --> 00:05:50,182
while you travel to any destination.      

94
00:05:59,226 --> 00:06:04,897
♪          

95
00:06:04,899 --> 00:06:08,968
narrator: horses need regular exercise to stay healthy and fit.    

96
00:06:08,970 --> 00:06:11,036
this innovative mechanical exerciser           

97
00:06:11,038 --> 00:06:15,307
provides horses with a safe way
to stay active on their own,  

98
00:06:15,309 --> 00:06:19,178
especially if they spend long 
periods of time in their stalls.

99
00:06:22,449 --> 00:06:25,050
the rotating panels of this exerciser           

100
00:06:25,052 --> 00:06:28,987
give horses the push they need to get moving.    

101
00:06:28,989 --> 00:06:31,924
an operator regulates the speed of the panel,    

102
00:06:31,926 --> 00:06:34,793
which controls the pace of the workout.        

103
00:06:34,795 --> 00:06:36,528
making this horse exerciser  

104
00:06:36,530 --> 00:06:39,398
starts with a computer-generated design.   

105
00:06:39,400 --> 00:06:43,135
this one is for a six-horse exerciser.     

106
00:06:43,137 --> 00:06:47,006
once designing is complete, production can begin.     

107
00:06:47,008 --> 00:06:50,009
first, a sheet of mile-carbon steel uncoils         

108
00:06:50,011 --> 00:06:52,344
into a rolling slitting machine.

109
00:06:52,346 --> 00:06:54,680
circular blades above and below slice        

110
00:06:54,682 --> 00:06:57,615
the steel sheet into strips.  

111
00:06:57,617 --> 00:07:01,620
most of the strips will be made
into structural tubing.    

112
00:07:01,622 --> 00:07:04,556
one of the strips enters a 300-foot-long machine    

113
00:07:04,558 --> 00:07:06,758
with many rollers.       

114
00:07:06,760 --> 00:07:11,563
the rollers shape the strip from flat to round.      

115
00:07:11,565 --> 00:07:14,499
more rollers shape the material.

116
00:07:14,501 --> 00:07:17,836
as an induction coil energized by a radio-frequency      

117
00:07:17,838 --> 00:07:21,707
electric current wields it together.          

118
00:07:21,709 --> 00:07:26,578
a blade shaves the excess steel
from the wielded steam.    

119
00:07:26,580 --> 00:07:28,647
meanwhile another tubing sheers

120
00:07:28,649 --> 00:07:31,649
the tubing against a set of guy
clamping blocks,        

121
00:07:31,651 --> 00:07:33,719
cutting it to the specified length.     

122
00:07:36,590 --> 00:07:40,659
finally, the tubing exits the cutting operation.     

123
00:07:40,661 --> 00:07:43,262
a technician wields both plates
to the tubing         

124
00:07:43,264 --> 00:07:45,664
and adds a cable-stabilizer bar.    

125
00:07:48,602 --> 00:07:51,136
the completed part will serve as one of the arms       

126
00:07:51,138 --> 00:07:55,541
that link the center shaft to the revolving panels.    

127
00:07:55,543 --> 00:07:57,609
another machinist builds the panels           

128
00:07:57,611 --> 00:08:00,879
for the exerciser's inner and outer walls.     

129
00:08:00,881 --> 00:08:04,616
to do so, he arranges tubing horizontally and inserts    

130
00:08:04,618 --> 00:08:07,619
a vertical support bar.    

131
00:08:07,621 --> 00:08:09,755
he wields a framework to the tubing         

132
00:08:09,757 --> 00:08:12,691
to hold the panel structure together.      

133
00:08:12,693 --> 00:08:15,894
he adds a steel shield to the lower part.       

134
00:08:15,896 --> 00:08:18,230
the shield will prevent sand from being forced       

135
00:08:18,232 --> 00:08:23,701
out of the exerciser track by the horses' hooves.     

136
00:08:23,703 --> 00:08:25,703
once construction is complete, 

137
00:08:25,705 --> 00:08:28,807
the technician stacks the assembled panels together. 

138
00:08:31,178 --> 00:08:33,178
next, an overhead monorail   

139
00:08:33,180 --> 00:08:36,348
transports the panels to the powder-coating station. 

140
00:08:40,654 --> 00:08:42,120
using an applicator,      

141
00:08:42,122 --> 00:08:45,657
a technician applies a powder coat to the revolving panels. 

142
00:08:45,659 --> 00:08:47,893
the powder coat provides an anti-corrosive       

143
00:08:47,895 --> 00:08:50,529
protective finish.       

144
00:08:50,531 --> 00:08:53,932
a team clamps one of the structural panels in a machine 

145
00:08:53,934 --> 00:08:56,201
with powerful mechanical arms. 

146
00:08:56,203 --> 00:09:00,739
the arms bend the panel to a specified curvature.   

147
00:09:00,741 --> 00:09:04,009
all the structural panels are bent to the same angle,  

148
00:09:04,011 --> 00:09:07,078
so that when looked, they'll form a round pen.   

149
00:09:07,080 --> 00:09:12,551
♪          

150
00:09:12,553 --> 00:09:14,152
using a press brake,      

151
00:09:14,154 --> 00:09:19,891
a technician makes two strategic
bends in a flat sheet of steel,

152
00:09:19,893 --> 00:09:22,728
which creates a flared three-walled part.       

153
00:09:26,633 --> 00:09:28,833
another machinist fits two of these parts         

154
00:09:28,835 --> 00:09:32,437
together to create a structure known as the tree.       

155
00:09:32,439 --> 00:09:34,907
then he wields connectors to the tree          

156
00:09:34,909 --> 00:09:37,276
for the cables and tubular arms.

157
00:09:40,648 --> 00:09:45,184
a loop is wielded on top for handling purposes.     

158
00:09:45,186 --> 00:09:47,719
then the tree is given a powder-coat finish to match 

159
00:09:47,721 --> 00:09:50,322
the rest of the horse-exerciser machine.

160
00:09:53,527 --> 00:09:56,861
using a hoist, a technician lowers the drive shaft     

161
00:09:56,863 --> 00:10:00,999
onto the motor and shakes the framework    

162
00:10:01,001 --> 00:10:03,302
to bring the connection into alignment.        

163
00:10:06,740 --> 00:10:09,674
then the assembly is tested to confirm the motor      

164
00:10:09,676 --> 00:10:11,343
turns the shaft.        

165
00:10:13,614 --> 00:10:17,149
steel panels fit to the framework to enclose the motor 

166
00:10:17,151 --> 00:10:20,686
and protect it from the elements.       

167
00:10:20,688 --> 00:10:24,622
he attaches a door, so the motor
can be accessed for maintenance.

168
00:10:24,624 --> 00:10:29,694
♪          

169
00:10:29,696 --> 00:10:32,865
now complete, the parts are ready for shipping.    

170
00:10:37,638 --> 00:10:40,438
on-site assembly takes about nine hours,          

171
00:10:40,440 --> 00:10:41,839
but it's well worth the wait  

172
00:10:41,841 --> 00:10:44,009
when the horses get to test it out.      

173
00:10:47,648 --> 00:10:49,247
halfway through the test,   

174
00:10:49,249 --> 00:10:51,850
the operator reverses the direction of the machine  

175
00:10:51,852 --> 00:10:54,253
to ensure all of the horses' muscles      

176
00:10:54,255 --> 00:10:58,524
are being exercised accordingly,

177
00:10:58,526 --> 00:11:02,494
proving that running around in circles can be a good thing.

178
00:11:13,807 --> 00:11:18,877
♪          

179
00:11:18,879 --> 00:11:22,748
narrator: air hockey was developed in the late '60s and early '70s

180
00:11:22,750 --> 00:11:25,817
by a group of american billiard engineers.

181
00:11:25,819 --> 00:11:29,421
when in play, the puck floats on a thin cushion of air,   

182
00:11:29,423 --> 00:11:31,757
propelled by players on each end.          

183
00:11:31,759 --> 00:11:34,959
with no friction, the puck moves fast,      

184
00:11:34,961 --> 00:11:39,097
making air hockey a high-speed game.       

185
00:11:39,099 --> 00:11:40,632
in a game of air hockey,    

186
00:11:40,634 --> 00:11:43,168
the puck levitates ever so slightly,       

187
00:11:43,170 --> 00:11:45,503
made possible by a constant flow of air   

188
00:11:45,505 --> 00:11:49,307
flowing through perforations in the playfield.       

189
00:11:49,309 --> 00:11:52,778
the playfield is made from a laminated composite material  

190
00:11:52,780 --> 00:11:57,382
that's been printed with air hockey graphics.   

191
00:11:57,384 --> 00:12:01,386
a computerized drill cuts into three playfields at once 

192
00:12:01,388 --> 00:12:03,422
in the same consistent pattern.

193
00:12:06,460 --> 00:12:09,794
the size of the holes are a little larger than pin holes,

194
00:12:09,796 --> 00:12:15,334
creating over 4,600 perforations
in each air hockey playfield. 

195
00:12:19,406 --> 00:12:21,539
an automated tool carves grooves

196
00:12:21,541 --> 00:12:25,744
in a sheet of medium density fiber board.      

197
00:12:25,746 --> 00:12:30,682
the board will serve as a base for the playfield.       

198
00:12:30,684 --> 00:12:33,151
air will circulate in the grooves and exit    

199
00:12:33,153 --> 00:12:35,687
through the playfield holes.  

200
00:12:35,689 --> 00:12:40,225
next, sawdust is blasted out of the grooves.      

201
00:12:40,227 --> 00:12:44,496
the grooves' fiberboard moves through a glue applicator.   

202
00:12:44,498 --> 00:12:46,765
the rubber roller coats the top of the board      

203
00:12:46,767 --> 00:12:48,634
with a small amount of glue,  

204
00:12:48,636 --> 00:12:51,069
so it doesn't seep into the grooves.       

205
00:12:53,307 --> 00:12:57,542
as the board exits, technicians
move the board onto a stack.  

206
00:13:00,247 --> 00:13:02,781
once the board is in the correct
position,           

207
00:13:02,783 --> 00:13:05,050
the laminate is applied    

208
00:13:05,052 --> 00:13:07,786
and aligned with the grooves in the fiber board.      

209
00:13:11,391 --> 00:13:14,993
a cardboard cover is placed on the laminate for protection 

210
00:13:14,995 --> 00:13:18,796
as the stack moves through a press.     

211
00:13:18,798 --> 00:13:21,733
the weight of the press squeezes the stack together,  

212
00:13:21,735 --> 00:13:24,569
ensuring adhesion as the glue cures.       

213
00:13:27,341 --> 00:13:30,608
meanwhile, a craftswoman applies
stick-on graphics       

214
00:13:30,610 --> 00:13:32,744
onto the side apron boards.  

215
00:13:36,282 --> 00:13:39,418
she opens a pre-cut slot for a coin door        

216
00:13:39,420 --> 00:13:41,653
and exposes a hole for a bolt. 

217
00:13:44,224 --> 00:13:47,091
she cuts open a slot for maintenance access     

218
00:13:47,093 --> 00:13:49,861
and removes the panel that will serve as a door.   

219
00:13:52,499 --> 00:13:55,167
she numbers the door and the side apron piece,   

220
00:13:55,169 --> 00:13:58,403
so she can match them up later during installation.      

221
00:14:01,374 --> 00:14:04,042
after applying art work to the end panels,       

222
00:14:04,044 --> 00:14:07,312
another technician assembles curved corner parts      

223
00:14:09,450 --> 00:14:12,718
and links mental brackets to the side apron parts.    

224
00:14:15,322 --> 00:14:17,789
he installs a bracket for a puck deflector      

225
00:14:17,791 --> 00:14:23,462
in the center of the end panel        

226
00:14:23,464 --> 00:14:25,931
and screws down the corner connectors.     

227
00:14:28,402 --> 00:14:31,169
he sets the end panels in an upside-down possession  

228
00:14:31,171 --> 00:14:34,338
on the work surface      

229
00:14:34,340 --> 00:14:37,743
and attaches the side boards to the corner connectors.   

230
00:14:40,214 --> 00:14:42,514
this completes the table apron.

231
00:14:45,486 --> 00:14:48,887
a locked door is installed in the plywood floor.     

232
00:14:48,889 --> 00:14:52,057
this will serve as an interior storage compartment.      

233
00:14:56,296 --> 00:14:59,231
next, a craftsman installs the coin door         

234
00:14:59,233 --> 00:15:01,233
and secures it into place.   

235
00:15:03,570 --> 00:15:06,771
he mounts wire speakers that projects sound effects  

236
00:15:06,773 --> 00:15:08,974
to a computerized optical system

237
00:15:08,976 --> 00:15:12,177
that tracks the puck's movements.     

238
00:15:12,179 --> 00:15:15,247
once the structure is fitted with wooden panels,      

239
00:15:15,249 --> 00:15:20,252
the game's flashing lights and 
sensor activators are installed.

240
00:15:20,254 --> 00:15:21,720
at another station,      

241
00:15:21,722 --> 00:15:26,324
a team flips a playfield over to work on the back.   

242
00:15:26,326 --> 00:15:29,594
one technician attaches a board
above the open grooves,    

243
00:15:29,596 --> 00:15:31,830
creating a chamber for airflow.

244
00:15:34,667 --> 00:15:38,136
the motor and fan are installed
over the small opening.    

245
00:15:38,138 --> 00:15:40,605
this system will blow air into the grooves        

246
00:15:40,607 --> 00:15:44,276
and the playfield perforations.

247
00:15:44,278 --> 00:15:46,211
the playfield is turned over  

248
00:15:46,213 --> 00:15:49,747
and lowered onto the table structure.      

249
00:15:49,749 --> 00:15:52,617
next, aluminum bumpers are attached to the table's  

250
00:15:52,619 --> 00:15:57,155
border as a barrier for the puck during play.   

251
00:15:57,157 --> 00:16:00,892
a technician installs goal puck
deflectors on the ends     

252
00:16:03,163 --> 00:16:08,300
and screws in metal plates over the deflector cups.    

253
00:16:08,302 --> 00:16:10,835
he installs a lock on each goal compartment    

254
00:16:10,837 --> 00:16:12,804
so no one can steal the puck. 

255
00:16:16,243 --> 00:16:20,177
finally, the air hockey table assembly is complete.  

256
00:16:20,179 --> 00:16:22,013
let the games begin.      

257
00:16:30,724 --> 00:16:36,528
♪          

258
00:16:36,530 --> 00:16:39,664
narrator: artisans have worked with copper for years. 

259
00:16:39,666 --> 00:16:44,068
the metal is soft enough to easily cut, shape, and emboss. 

260
00:16:44,070 --> 00:16:47,004
unless sealed, copper's bright,
shiny surface         

261
00:16:47,006 --> 00:16:49,274
naturally tarnishes over time, 

262
00:16:49,276 --> 00:16:53,578
producing a warm, aged finish, referred to as patina.     

263
00:16:57,283 --> 00:16:58,884
these intricate copper sculptures           

264
00:16:58,886 --> 00:17:03,488
are the work of an artist with a quirky imagination.   

265
00:17:03,490 --> 00:17:07,892
this style of work is designed to rotate on rods as lawn art 

266
00:17:07,894 --> 00:17:10,295
or weather vanes.       

267
00:17:10,297 --> 00:17:12,531
when a customer commissions a sculpture,          

268
00:17:12,533 --> 00:17:15,433
the artist draws the sculpture on cardstock,         

269
00:17:15,435 --> 00:17:17,168
a thick type of paper.     

270
00:17:21,375 --> 00:17:24,376
when planning a spinning sculpture like this griffin,  

271
00:17:24,378 --> 00:17:26,711
the artist sketches the side view.         

272
00:17:29,249 --> 00:17:30,848
using a pair of scissors,   

273
00:17:30,850 --> 00:17:33,251
he cuts off the excess cardstock.     

274
00:17:33,253 --> 00:17:39,190
♪          

275
00:17:39,192 --> 00:17:41,192
then he uses smaller scissors 

276
00:17:41,194 --> 00:17:44,329
to cut precisely along the lines of his drawing.   

277
00:17:44,331 --> 00:17:51,335
♪          

278
00:17:51,337 --> 00:17:53,939
now the artist has a pattern to work with.  

279
00:17:57,277 --> 00:17:59,911
he lays the pattern on a sheet of copper,     

280
00:18:02,883 --> 00:18:04,282
tapes it down,         

281
00:18:06,552 --> 00:18:08,687
and traces it with a fine-point pen     

282
00:18:08,689 --> 00:18:10,821
to get a crisp line.      

283
00:18:10,823 --> 00:18:13,825
the tracing must be precise for the sculpture's components 

284
00:18:13,827 --> 00:18:16,361
to line up properly.      

285
00:18:16,363 --> 00:18:19,230
he repeats this step on a second sheet of copper,  

286
00:18:19,232 --> 00:18:22,566
since the sculpture will be two-sided.       

287
00:18:22,568 --> 00:18:26,905
he cuts along the line with metal sheers.       

288
00:18:26,907 --> 00:18:29,440
first, he cuts away the excess copper       

289
00:18:29,442 --> 00:18:32,377
and then does the detailed cutting.     

290
00:18:32,379 --> 00:18:37,315
he cuts out pieces for the left
and right side of the sculpture.

291
00:18:37,317 --> 00:18:41,652
the artist draws an eye on the back of the right-side head.  

292
00:18:41,654 --> 00:18:44,188
with a round-head hammer, he taps a piece of       

293
00:18:44,190 --> 00:18:47,759
stainless-steel wire      
on the line to create an eyelid.

294
00:18:50,330 --> 00:18:54,332
he uses tools designed for stamping leather.     

295
00:18:54,334 --> 00:18:57,802
he recesses the head, so that on the reverse side,  

296
00:18:57,804 --> 00:19:01,473
the front of the sculpture, the head will appear raised.  

297
00:19:04,343 --> 00:19:06,878
this technique brings dimension
and texture          

298
00:19:06,880 --> 00:19:10,215
to what was originally a flat piece of copper.    

299
00:19:10,217 --> 00:19:12,350
the artist hammers the back of the wing          

300
00:19:12,352 --> 00:19:15,487
to gradually contour and texture the feathers.   

301
00:19:18,825 --> 00:19:21,826
he uses different tools to create finer effects    

302
00:19:21,828 --> 00:19:23,895
such as veining.        

303
00:19:23,897 --> 00:19:26,898
this age-old technique of hammering a malleable metal 

304
00:19:26,900 --> 00:19:30,034
from the reverse side to create a design in relief  

305
00:19:30,036 --> 00:19:35,306
is called repoussé, french for "pushed back".   

306
00:19:35,308 --> 00:19:37,842
the artist heats a part with a torch          

307
00:19:37,844 --> 00:19:41,446
and applies zinc chloride flux to the parameter.       

308
00:19:41,448 --> 00:19:44,048
this caustic solution cleans the copper,          

309
00:19:44,050 --> 00:19:47,686
removing impurities that would prevent solder from adhering. 

310
00:19:51,124 --> 00:19:54,658
then he uses a blowtorch to melt silver-based solder  

311
00:19:54,660 --> 00:19:55,793
onto the copper,        

312
00:19:55,795 --> 00:19:57,862
around the parameter of the part.   

313
00:20:02,802 --> 00:20:05,203
this step is called pre-soldering,         

314
00:20:05,205 --> 00:20:08,139
as the sculpture will be fully soldered later. 

315
00:20:08,141 --> 00:20:16,347
♪          

316
00:20:16,349 --> 00:20:18,616
he pre-solders the back of the pieces         

317
00:20:18,618 --> 00:20:21,619
that will be attached to matching pieces.      

318
00:20:21,621 --> 00:20:23,688
then he heats the front surface

319
00:20:23,690 --> 00:20:27,224
to bring out a rainbow of colors.      

320
00:20:27,226 --> 00:20:29,627
next, he aligns the matching parts       

321
00:20:29,629 --> 00:20:31,629
and heats them with a torch.  

322
00:20:31,631 --> 00:20:34,032
this melts the solder along the
parameter,           

323
00:20:34,034 --> 00:20:36,901
fusing the pieces together.  

324
00:20:36,903 --> 00:20:40,438
in areas where the sides are too
far apart to be fused,     

325
00:20:40,440 --> 00:20:45,042
he solders a small copper patch
to fit over the gap.      

326
00:20:45,044 --> 00:20:48,580
he flattens all the seams with fine grinding tools    

327
00:20:48,582 --> 00:20:51,649
until they appear seamless.  

328
00:20:51,651 --> 00:20:56,387
he repeats this process for each section of the sculpture. 

329
00:20:56,389 --> 00:20:58,656
once all the sections are assembled,         

330
00:20:58,658 --> 00:21:00,725
he solders them to each other. 

331
00:21:04,397 --> 00:21:06,531
the wing fits into a thin channel         

332
00:21:06,533 --> 00:21:08,933
he hammered into the body of the sculpture.       

333
00:21:08,935 --> 00:21:10,935
he melts the solder in the channel         

334
00:21:10,937 --> 00:21:13,138
to produce a neat and even seam.

335
00:21:13,140 --> 00:21:20,078
♪          

336
00:21:20,080 --> 00:21:24,148
to display the copper sculpture
or use it as a weather vane,  

337
00:21:24,150 --> 00:21:26,083
the artist solders a ball bearing         

338
00:21:26,085 --> 00:21:28,019
inside a copper tube,     

339
00:21:28,021 --> 00:21:33,091
then attaches the tube to the bottom of the sculpture.

340
00:21:33,093 --> 00:21:34,826
the tube slides over a rod,  

341
00:21:34,828 --> 00:21:38,329
so it can be set in the ground or mounted on the roof.    

